  "question": "A new program had 60 downloads in the first month. The number of downloads in the second month was three times as many as the downloads in the first month, but then reduced by 30% in the third month. How many downloads did the program have total over the three months?",
  "prompt": "A new program had 60 downloads in the first month. The number of downloads in the second month was three times as many as the downloads in the first month, but then reduced by 30% in the third month. How many downloads did the program have total over the three months?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "366",
  "generated_text": "To find the total number of downloads over the three months, we will calculate the number of downloads for each month step-by-step.\n\n1.  **First Month:**\n    The problem states there were 60 downloads.\n    $$ \\text{Downloads}_1 = 60 $$\n\n2.  **Second Month:**\n    The number of downloads was three times as many as the first month.\n    $$ \\text{Downloads}_2 = 3 \\times 60 = 180 $$\n\n3.  **Third Month:**\n    The number of downloads was reduced by 30% from the second month's amount.\n    First, calculate the reduction amount: $30\\%$ of $180$.\n    $$ \\text{Reduction} = 0.30 \\times 180 = 54 $$\n    Now, subtract the reduction from the second month's total to get the third month's downloads:\n    $$ \\text{Downloads}_3 = 180 - 54 = 126 $$\n    (Alternatively, calculating the reduction directly: $180 - 0.30(180) = 180 \\times (1 - 0.30) = 180 \\times 0.70 = 126$).\n\n4.  **Total Over Three Months:**\n    Add the downloads from all three months together.\n    $$ \\text{Total} = \\text{Downloads}_1 + \\text{Downloads}_2 + \\text{Downloads}_3 $$\n    $$ \\text{Total} = 60 + 180 + 126 $$\n    $$ \\text{Total} = 240 + 126 $$\n    $$ \\text{Total} = 366 $$\n\n\\boxed{366}\n",
